There have been increasing calls for security companies to beef up the protection of guards and improve their training. JOHANNESBURG - The Motor Transport Workers Union (MTWU) says more needs to be done to protect drivers of cash-in-transit vehicles. This follows another attack on a cash van in Limpopo on Monday, where seven suspects have been arrested. There have been increasing calls for security companies to beef up the protection of guards and improve their training. Union spokesperson Hlasinyane Motaung says they will be taking their issues to the government. “We will demonstrate on 11 June to highlight that we also want to be better equipped. On 13 June, we’ll meet with the portfolio committee in Parliament before strategising our next move.” (Edited by Zamangwane Shange)